    "cell": "At the cellular level, the relevant events are in the Gram-negative envelope. OmpK35 and OmpK36 reside in the outer membrane and govern entry into the periplasm. Cefoxitin acts in the periplasm by targeting PBPs involved in peptidoglycan synthesis. Reduced outer-membrane entry therefore decreases access to the target compartment. The beta-lactamases, if expressed, act in the periplasm after entry. No upstream porin regulators are explicitly reported in the visible evidence, so regulator-based loss is not the primary assigned mechanism.",
    "phenotype": "Because cefoxitin uptake is restricted by defective/narrowed major porins, the periplasmic drug concentration is reduced below that needed for reliable PBP inhibition. Background beta-lactamase activity may further lower the fraction of intact drug that reaches PBPs. The net result is failure of cefoxitin to sufficiently block cell-wall synthesis, yielding the observed resistant AST phenotype."
